               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Gregorian" notAfter="1450" notBefore="1400">15th century, first half</origDate>
                     <origPlace>
                        <country key="place_7002445">England</country>
                     </origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  
                  <provenance>On fol. 236v, there is a note in a late fifteenth-century hand in which <persName key="person_3690">Richard Merton</persName>, 'chanon', denies the 'malicious' charge brought against him by 'Marget Mukkulton' that he multiplied words
                     about the burning of Thomas Donsturfyld's ('where as hyt was alegyt agaynyst me by the malytyose mynde of marget mukkulton to myltiply wordys as conceminge the bronunge of 
                     thomas donsturfyld howse whyc I vtterly deny by fathe and pristehode neuer to speke to hym in the cause nor neuer to haue knolege in cause lyk that hyt sholde be soo.'); 
                     see Elizabeth Solopova, 
                        'Manuscript Evidence for the Patronage, Ownership and Use of the Wycliffite Bible' in 
                     <title><ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/434020/bodleian_library_western_medieval_manuscripts_bibliography/tags/MS.%20Bodl.%20531/items/F8M8GCLX/item-list">
                        Form and Function in the Late Medieval Bible</ref></title>, pp. 345-346</provenance>
                  
                  <provenance notBefore="1500" notAfter="1599">'<persName role="sgn" key="person_3691">John Auncelle</persName>, <persName role="sgn" key="person_3692">T. Levrett</persName> off Chearnys', '<persName role="sgn" key="person_3693">Mary Pygotte</persName>' were added on fol. 187v in the 16th century</provenance> <!-- Charnes, Eccleshall, Staffs?  -->
                  
                  
                  <acquisition when="1603">This volume seems to be the only one which corresponds to a gift of <persName key="person_51973268">Sir Edwin Sandys</persName> 
                     of London in 1603, but it escaped the printed catalogue of 1605. See also: <ref target="https://data.cerl.org/owners/00014161">Owners of Incunabula</ref></acquisition>
                  
